## High value, low effort

## Medium value

- [ ] --context-reports N
      Currently the previous report is always the single most recent. Passing N=3
      would include the last N reports as assistant messages, giving the AI a trend
      over multiple runs rather than just one comparison point.

## Bigger lift

- [ ] Scheduled daemon mode (--every 24h)
      Runs on a loop so you don't need a cron job. Uses time.sleep between runs.

- [ ] Email delivery
      Send the full report text via SMTP in addition to the Discord summary embed.
      Useful for archiving or reaching people not on Discord.

- [ ] --compare [FILE1] [FILE2]
      Pass two report filenames to the AI and ask it to summarise what changed
      between them. Useful for post-incident review or tracking a trend between
      two specific points in time.

- [ ] Config file support (~/.grafana_ai.toml)
      Persist defaults like window, model, and alert_threshold so the command line
      stays clean for daily use. CLI flags override config file values.

## Completed

- [x] --dry-run flag
      Fetch and process Grafana data, print dataset size and a sample, then exit
      without calling OpenAI. Free way to verify the Grafana connection and preview
      what the AI would receive.

- [x] --no-discord flag
      Skip the webhook even when DISCORD_WEBHOOK_URL is set. Useful for ad-hoc
      runs where you don't want to spam the channel.

- [x] --show-report [filename]
      Print a saved report to stdout. Without an argument, show the most recent one.

- [x] --list-reports
      List saved reports with filename, window, and file size. Simple wrapper
      around REPORT_DIR.glob.

- [x] Previous window mismatch warning
      If the loaded previous report was run with a different --window, note it in
      the AI user message so the comparison isn't silently misleading (e.g.
      comparing a 24h analysis to a previous 7d one).

- [x] Severity-based exit code
      Exit 0 if highest severity is LOW or LOWEST, exit 1 if MEDIUM, exit 2 if
      HIGH or HIGHEST. Makes the tool usable in alerting pipelines and shell
      conditionals without parsing the report text.

- [x] --quiet flag
      Suppress all progress lines (loaded previous report, forwarding to OpenAI…).
      Only the report itself and errors are printed. Useful in cron jobs where
      noisy stdout is unwanted.

- [x] --since FILENAME
      Use a specific saved report as the previous-report context instead of always
      the most recent. Lets you compare against a known-good baseline rather than
      whatever ran last.

- [x] --alert-threshold SEVERITY
      Only fire the Discord webhook when the report contains at least the given
      severity level (e.g. MEDIUM). Cuts noise on clean days where everything is
      LOW/LOWEST.

- [x] --prompt-extra "text"
      Append a free-form note to the AI user message so the model can account for
      known events (e.g. --prompt-extra "Maintenance window ran 02:00-04:00 UTC,
      ignore the traffic drop").

- [x] --output FILE
      Write the report to an explicit path instead of the auto-named file in
      REPORT_DIR. Handy for one-off runs you want to keep separate from the
      regular archive.
